Bring a large #saucepan{} of @water{100%ml} to the boil with @salt{0.25%tsp} for the rice.

When boiling, add the @basmati rice{150%g} and cook for ~{12%minutes}.

Drain in a #sieve{} and return to the saucepan, cover with a #lid{} until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve the @green chilli{1/2}(halved and deseeded), deseed then finely chop.

Chop the @paneer{250%g} into 2cm chunks.

> MOD Step 2: If you've chosen paneer instead of chicken, chop the paneer into 2cm chunks in the step above.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{}.

Once hot, add the paneer and stir fry until turning golden, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the onion and continue to cook, stirring, until the onion is softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add the @korma curry paste{50%g}, garlic, half the green chilli (add less if you don't like heat!), and @tomato puree{30%g}.

Cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}, then add the @tomato passata{150%g}, water and @vegetable stock powder{1} then bring to a simmer.

Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} and simmer until thickened, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all).

Add the @baby spinach{100%g} to the sauce a handful at a time until wilted.

Bring to the boil and simmer until the sauce has reduced slightly and the flavours have developed, ~{3-4%minutes}.

When everything is ready, stir the @mango chutney{40%g} and half the coriander through the curry.

Taste and season with more salt and pepper if you like.

Stir the remaining coriander through the rice.

Divide the rice and curry between your #bowls{}.

Top with the remaining green chilli.

Enjoy!

> MOD Step 3: If you've chosen paneer instead of diced chicken thigh, just cook the paneer in the same way the recipe tells you to cook the diced thigh in the step above and in the rest of the recipe.